The databricks command-line interface — validate, deploy, run, and destroy.

Four subcommands cover the entire bundle workflow.

Validate parses the manifest, resolves the variables for your chosen target, checks all the resource references, and emits the fully-resolved definition that would be sent to the A-P-I. You run it first, and you run it in continuous integration on every pull request.

Deploy uploads your notebooks and source files to the workspace, and creates or updates every resource — jobs, pipelines, volumes, schemas — so the workspace matches the manifest. It's idempotent, so re-deploying an unchanged bundle is a no-op.

Run kicks off a one-off run of a specific resource, like a job or a pipeline, and tails its output — it's the continuous-integration equivalent of clicking run-now in the interface.

And destroy removes all the resources the bundle owns from the target workspace. Use it carefully — but it's exactly what you want for tearing down an ephemeral test environment. So a typical local loop is validate against dev, deploy to dev, then run the job against dev.
